<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911111-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>911111-0054.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Rolls-Royce PLC:   McDonnell Agrees to Offer   Trent Engine as an Option</HL><DATE>11/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MD U.RR</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Britain's Rolls-Royce PLC said the U.S. aircraftmanufacturer McDonnell Douglas Corp. agreed to offerRolls-Royce's Trent engine as an option on the MD-12long-range airliner, scheduled to enter service in late 1995.   The agreement doesn't represent a sales pact between theaircraft-engine manufacturer and McDonnell Douglas. The U.S.manufacturer is expected to offer various other aircraftengines as options. However, Rolls-Royce is the first enginemanufacturer to reach an agreement with McDonnell Douglas toprovide a specific engine as an option. McDonnell Douglas hasforecast sales of 850 of the 375-passenger MD-12 aircraft.</LP><TEXT>   Rolls-Royce, which was hit recently by news that BritishAirways PLC had selected engines from General Electric Co. topower Boeing aircraft, declined to forecast its expectedsales for MD-12 aircraft. It has reached agreements with fourother airlines and an aircraft leasing concern amounting to178 Trent engines, 100 of which are &quot;firm,&quot; totaling nearly#1 billion ($1.77 billion).</TEXT></DOC>